1 R Graphics

  • High-level plotting functions create a new plot on the graphics device, possibly with axes, labels, titles and so on.
  • Low-level plotting functions add more information to an existing plot, such as extra points, lines and labels.

1.1 High-level plotting functions

  • pairs(data) #scatterplot between all variables
  • hist(x)
  • boxplot(x) and boxplot(y~x)
  • plot (x,y, ...) #produce a scatterplot according to x and y coordinates
    • type #indicates type of plot (points, line, both, …).
    • axes #indicates whether axes should be plotted
    • xlim ylim #specify the limits of the x- and y-axes.
    • main xlab ylab #specify the main and axes titles
    • plot(density(norm.s) #plot density

Examples:

  1. hist(data.frame$variable.x) – plot histrogram of variable X
  2. plot(y~x) or plot(data.frame$variable.x, data.frame$varaible.y) – plot x against y

1.2 Low-level plotting functions

  • col #color
  • points(x, y, pch=1, cex=1, col=1)
    • pch #plot character
    • cex #character expansion (relative size)
  • lines(x, y, lty=1, lwd=1)
    • lty #line type
    • lwd #line width
  • Setting for axis annotation, axis and main titles
    • cex.axis, cex.lab, cex.main
    • font.lab=2 …Bold the axis label

1.2.1 Other plotting commands

  • text(x, y, “text”) … adds “text” at x, y
  • abline(a, b) … adds line of intercept a, slope b
    • abline(h=y) … adds a horizontal line at y
    • abline(v=x) … adds a vertical line at x
  • polygon(x, y) … adds a polygon with corners at each xi, yi (x and y should be vectors)
  • legend(x, y, text) … adds a legend at x,y
  • title(“title text”) … adds a title (same effect as “main”)

1.2.2 Adding an axis

  • axis(side, pos, at, labels)
    • side =1 for bottom, 2 for left, 3 for top, 4 for right
    • pos = positioning of axis
    • at = where tick marks should be drawn
    • labels = what to write next to each tick mark
    • For a y-axis add the option las=1 to get horizontal rather than vertical text labels (looks nicer!)
      • axis(1, pos=11, at=0:5, labels=0:5)…This adds an x-axis at the horizontal location y=11 with tick marks at x=0,1,…,5 and corresponding labels.

1.2.3 Further customisation

  • par() … used to access and modify graphics parameters for the current device
    • par(col=“red”, lty=2) … change the default colour to red and the default line type to 2 (dotted)
    • par(mar=c(5,4,1,1)) … change the default plot margins to 5,4,1,1 on the bottom, left, top, right (the default is 5,4,2,2)
  • Plot windows
    • windows(width=6, height=5) …Opens a new graphics window with width=6 inches and height=5 inches
      • quartz(“Quartz”, width=6 , height=5) [for Mac OS]
    • par(mfrow=c(2,2)) / par(mfcol=c(2,2))
      • Split the graphics window evenly into 4 subplots (divide the window to 2 rows and 2 columns)
      • shown in an order by rows (mfrow) or columns (mfcol)
    • layout(matrix(1:4, nrow=2, byrow=TRUE), widths=c(1,1), heights=c(1,3))
      • Split the graphics window into 4 subplots where the top two occupy 25% and bottom two occupy 75% of the plot region,respectively
      • widths, heights #specify ratio between 2 plots

1.2.4 Example: MVC data

1.3 Save graphical output

  • pdf(file, width, height) … this will start the graphics device driver
    • file is the filename and its directory
    • can also save in other format: e.g. bmp, jpeg, png, tiff
  • dev.off()
    • close the graphics device
    ##EXAMPLE
pdf("figure1.pdf", width=6, height=4) #open a flat sheet
plot(MVC ~ age, data=mvc) #draw a plot on a flat sheet
dev.off() #close the file

2.3 Bar graph

  1. stat_"bin" …The count of cases for each group
  2. stat_"identity"…The value of a column in the data set
  • geom_bar …Basic bar graph
    • fill=variable.x…Map variable x to different fill colors
    • colour=black…Add a black outline
    • Example: ggplot(data=dat, aes(x=time, y=total_bill, fill=time)) + geom_bar(colour="black", stat="identity") + guides(fill=FALSE)
  • geom_line…Basic line graph
    • group=1…All points should be grouped so all points are connected
    • geom_point()…Add points
    • Example: ggplot(data=dat, aes(x=time, y=total_bill, group=1)) + geom_line(colour="red", linetype="dashed", size=1.5) + geom_point(colour="red", size=4, shape=21, fill="white")

3 Generating random numbers

Draw random samples from discrete / continuous probability distributions e.g. Uniform distribution, simulate what will happen in 10 households in disease outbreak

3.1 Uniform Distribution

  • runif(n, min, max)…Random number with uniform distribution

    • n is the number of samples
    • min / max are the lower and upper limits of the uniform distribution

  • Useful for simulation of random process

    unif.s<-runif(1000,min=1,max=3)
hist(unif.s) #It's even/uniform distribution

3.2 Binomial distribution

  • rbinom(n, size, prob)

    • n is the number of samples
    • size is the number of trials
    • prob is the probability of success for each trial
    binom.s <- rbinom(1000, size=10, prob=0.4)
hist(binom.s, main="Distribution of 1000 binomia samples", freq=F, las=1) #expect the mean to be 4

    #rbinom(10, 1,.5)
#[1] 1 0 1 1 1 0 0 0 0 1

3.3 Normal distribution

  • rnorm(n, mean, sd)
    • n is the number of samples
    • mean is the mean / vector of means
    • sd is the standard deviation / vector of standard deviations
    norm.s <- rnorm(1000, mean=0, sd=1)
plot(density(norm.s), main="Distribution of 1000 normal samples", las=1)

3.4 Random sample

  • sample(x, size, replace, prob)
    • x is a vector from which samples are drawn
    • size is the number of samples to be drawn
    • replace indicates if the samples are drawn with replacement
    • prob specify the probability of selecting each x
    sample(seq(1,50), 10, replace=F)
sample(1:5,20,replace=T,prob=c(0.1,0.35,0.1,0.35,0.1))
    ##  [1] 29 11 37 24 36 21 39  8 28 31
##  [1] 2 1 3 5 2 4 2 2 2 1 4 2 2 2 2 1 4 2 4 2

3.5 Specify “seed” for randomization

  • Seed is an integer which specifies the state of random number generator

  • Ensure the result change due to change of script but not random number

    set.seed(111)
runif(3)
    ## [1] 0.5929813 0.7264811 0.3704220
    set.seed(111)
runif(3)
    ## [1] 0.5929813 0.7264811 0.3704220

4 Linear regression in R

  • If Y is the response variable and X is the explanatory variable, then a simple linear regression states that \(Y = α + βX + ε\)
    • ε is distributed N(0, σ2), so that \(Y \sim\ {\sf Norm}(α + βX, σ^{2})\)
  • When there is more than one explanatory variable, i.e. more than one X, then the linear regression is not “simple”, but “multiple”.
    • Now \(Y \sim\ {\sf Norm} (α + β_{1}X_{1} + β_{2}X_{2} + … +β_{k}X_{k}, σ^{2})\)
  • Can also include interactions, i.e. terms where two or more of the explanatory variables are multiplied together, and higher-order powers of the variables, e.g. X12, X1X2

  • lm(formula, data, subset, weights, na.action…)
    • formula is written as y~x+z
    • data indicates the data frame to be used
    • subset indicates that only some of the data should be used, e.g. subset=(gender==“M”) #Only fit regression model in male; when gender equals to male, we fit the model
    • weights weights the observations
    • na.action describes what to do with missing data. The default is na.omit (listwise deletion) #default is removing missing data from analysis
    mvc <- read.csv("Folder/mvc.CSV")
##Fit linear regression model
#summary(lm(MVC ~ height + age, data=mvc))

#Or in separate steps:
mvc.lm <- lm(MVC ~ height + age, data=mvc)
mvc.lm #The estimated regression equation is: MVC = -465.63 + 5.40 × height – 3.08 × age
summary(mvc.lm) #Provide more info like sd, p , r-square

##Extract result
mvc.lm$coef #Extract coefficient
summary(mvc.lm)$coef[2,] #Call out specific numbers to get more accurate result

##tell u what are stored in regression output
names(mvc.lm)

4.1 Convert numeric to factor (categorizing)

  • cut(x, breaks, labels = NULL, include.lowest = FALSE, right = TRUE, ...)
    • x is the variable to be converted to factor, e.g. age
    • breaks defines the cut point
    • labels gives the label for each category level
    • right = TRUE indicates the intervals should be close on the right, i.e., intervals of ( ].
    • include.lowest = TRUE includes values at the first (when right = TRUE) or last (when right = FALSE) cut point with an open interval
    • Default ref group is the first grouop…x is the categorical variable to be re-ordered
      • relevel(x, ref) …only ref group is changed
      • factor(x, levels) …levels is the specified order, re-order every groups
    x = 1:8
#Categorize x
cut(x,c(1,3,6,8)) #1 is not categorized
cut(x,c(0,3,5,8)) #1 is categorized
cut(x,c(1,3,5,8), include.lowest=TRUE) #1 is categorized

#Label the groups
x <- cut(x,c(1,3,5,8), label=c('low','med','high'), include.lowest=TRUE) 

#Change ref group or oder
relevel(x, ref='med')
factor(x, c('high','med','low'))

4.2 Confidence intervals for the estimated coefficients

  • The two-sided 100(1-α)% confidence interval (CI) of an estimated coefficient β is given by \(β ± t(1-\frac{α}{2}, n-k) × s_{β}\)
    • where t(1-α/2, n-k) is the critical value of the student’s distribution with degree of freedom n-k
      • for α = 0.05, t(0.975, n-k) → z(0.975) = 1.96 when n is large (t distribution close to standard normal distribution when df is large)
    • k is the number of parameters in the model including the intercept
    • sβ is the standard error of the estimated coefficient
    • In R, confint(): profile likelihood CI, confint.default(): Wald CI
      • 2 different theories
        • Profile liklihood CI consider all different parameters
        • Wald: consistent with the p-values in the regression summary table
#Obtain 95%CI
confint(mvc.lm)

#Alternatively (not explained in lecture)
mvc.out <- summary(mvc.lm)
mvc.out
mvc.out$coef[,"Estimate"] %o% c(1,1) + mvc.out$coef[,"Std.Error"] %o% qt(c(0.025,0.975), mvc.out$df[2])

4.3 Compare model with AIC

AIC(model1,model2) …model with lower AIC is better
Need a large difference (2/4) to accept more complicated model, otherwise use parsimonious model.

4.4 Stepwise selection for model

stepAIC(model, direction)

  • Stepwise selection according to AIC.
  • both = perform both backward and forward model selection
    • Example: For the model in tutorial 1 with predictors age, height and height2, height is removed coz results in lower AIC on statistcal means

4.5 Fit new data to the model

#define new observation
new <- data.frame(age=50, height=170)

#use fitted model to predict the response value for the new observation
predict(lm.mvc4, new, interval = "prediction") #generate prediction interval

5 Check normality for a set of data

shapiro.test(data) …when p-value <0.05, we reject normal distribution

6 IF and FOR statement

  • if (condition) statement1 else statement2
    • condition is evaluated
    • statement1 will be executed if the condition is TRUE
    • else, statement2 will be executed
    • (grouped statement is enclosed within braces {})
    x <- 5
if (x > 0) print ("x is non-negative!") else print ("x is negative")
    ## [1] "x is non-negative!"
  • for (variable in sequence) statement
    • variable is the loop variable
    • sequence is the vector of values for variable within the loop
    x <- 0
for (i in 1:10){
x <- x + i
}
x
    ## [1] 55
    sum(1:10)
    ## [1] 55
